				Object
			========================
			========================

a physical existence of class 

we can have any number of objects for a class 


				Syntax of Objects
			==============================

OjectReferenceVariable=ClassName( )

ReferenceVariable----   The Varaible which can be used to refer object is Called reference variable


		

Note----To call variables and functions from a class we use object or ObjectReference variable 
	



Ex-

class Bank:

	def Name(self):
		print("Bank Name is Canara")

	

>>>b1=Bank()
>>>Bank().Name() 	# Bank Name is Canara     ------>Using Object
>>>b1.name( )	        # Bank Name is Canara     ------>Using ObjectReferenceVariable



Calling variables and Methods from class--
========================================================================


1----With Objects
==============================



>>>Bank( ).display( )	#Bank Name is Canara

Note-----

	By using object we can call only one variable or one function for one time only (Not Second time)	


2-----With Object Reference Variable
=================================
=================================

>>>b1.display( )		#Bank Name is Canara


Note -----

	By using object reference variable we can call multiple variables and multiple functions 
	for any Number of Times
===================================================================================
===================================================================================



self variable--->
==============
==============

	self is the default variable which is always pointing to current objects
	by using self we can access instance variable and instance method of object.


Ex--->

	def __init__(self ):			#inside a constructor 

	def  name (self):			#inside a instance method

==================================================================================
==================================================================================


				Constructor
==================================================================================
			
			


1). Constructor is special method in python
2). Constructor is used to initialize instance variable of a class
3). Constructor name should be __init__(self )
4). Constructor is automatically called at time of object creation
5). Per object constructor will be executed only once
6). Constructor will take self as default parameter
7). Constructor can be Parameterized and Nonparameterized

Ex
=====
=====
	class Bank:
		def __init__(self):
			print("This is Constructor")

>>>b=Bank()		# This is Constructor


1--Parameterized Constructor
==================================================

this constructor takes parameter during object creation

>>>class Employee:

	def __init__(self,name,company,city):
			self.name=name
			self.company=company
			self.city=city
	def  display(self):
		print(self.name)
		print(self.company)
		print(self.city)

>>>e1=Employee( )		                #Error required 3 arguments

>>>e2=Employee("Shubham","XYZ","Banglore")		
>>>e2.display( )				#Shubham XYZ Banglore


>>>e3=Employee("Saurabh","Hospital","Home")		
>>>e3.display( )				#Saurabh Hospital Home



2---NonParameterized
===================
===================

This doesnot take any parameter during object creation

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CASE 1
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
>>> class Employee:
	def __init__(self,name="Shubham",age="25"):
		self.name=name
		self.age=age
	def  display(self):
		print(self.name)
		print(self.age)

		
>>> e1=Employee( )
>>> e1.display( )		# Shubham 25


>>> e2=Employee( )
>>> e2.display( )		# Shubham 25



>>> e3=Employee("xyz",22 )           {While, It can take parameter, If passed in this way of coding}
>>> e3.display( )		# xyz 22


------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CASE 2
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

>>> class Employee:
	def __init__(self):
		self.name="Shubham"
		self.age="22"
	def  display(self):
		print(self.name)
		print(self.age)
	

		
>>> e1=Employee( )
>>> e1.display( )	#Shubham 22


>>> e2=Employee( )
>>> e2.display( )	#Shubham 22


>>> e3=Employee("shb",332 )           {While, It cannot take any parameter, in such case}
>>> e3.display( )		# ---> e2=Employee("shb",332 ) 
           			       e2.display( )
				       TypeError: __init__() takes 1 positional argument but 3 were given



----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

		NonParameterized and Parameterized Both Defining
	================================================================
	================================================================


>>> class Employee:
	def __init__(self,name="Shubham",age="120"):
		self.name=name
		self.age=age
	def  display(self):
		print(self.name)
		print(self.age)

		
>>> e1=Employee( )
>>> e1.display( )	#Shubham 120


>>> e2=Employee("Saurabh","18")
>>> e2.display()	#Saurabh 18


>>> e3=Employee("40")
>>> e3.display( ) 		# 40 120



>>> e4=Employee(age="40")
>>> e4.display( ) 		# Shubham 40

>>> e5=Employee(name="Gaurabh")
>>> e5.display()			# Gaurabh  120




